                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="12766524" author="srowen" created="Fri, 16 Oct 2009 14:22:27 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Since I&apos;m looking at this &amp;#8211; what&apos;s the rationale? I understand the concept of signing but is signing the overall release not covering this?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12766540" author="gsingers" created="Fri, 16 Oct 2009 15:20:53 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Every artifact we release, we have to sign so that people can verify them.  I would, first, however, look into Hadoop&apos;s publication to Maven of its JARs and dependencies.  Doing that would take care of, I believe, this issue b/c then we wouldn&apos;t have to install our own versions.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12766548" author="srowen" created="Fri, 16 Oct 2009 15:46:10 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;I see so these count as artifacts that get published separately? I see, thought we basically published our tarball, and .jars to Maven, and that was it.&lt;br/&gt;
I will look into said Hadoop dependency.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12766884" author="gsingers" created="Sat, 17 Oct 2009 12:22:46 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Yeah, they are, to some extent our artifacts.  It&apos;s really not a big deal.  All the signature really does is allow someone to verify that what they downloaded is the thing that we uploaded.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12767620" author="srowen" created="Tue, 20 Oct 2009 00:49:12 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;I am tentatively resolving this as it seems to sign artifacts &amp;#8211; will look at what happens when I run the release.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
